WEBVTT

00:00.962 --> 00:04.125
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.686 --> 00:18.380
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.121 --> 00:26.649
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.709 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:36.002
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:40.749 --> 00:41.370
Peace be with you.

00:41.410 --> 00:45.296
Friends, we come to this third Sunday of Advent called Gaudete Sunday.

00:45.916 --> 00:48.701
Let's say an imperative in Latin, meaning rejoice.

00:48.741 --> 00:50.263
It's a command to rejoice.

00:51.184 --> 00:55.030
You know what strikes me about the readings this week and this year?

00:55.070 --> 00:57.874
Is there really good at helping us

00:58.466 --> 01:01.070
Understand what to do while we wait.

01:01.691 --> 01:06.258
I talked a couple weeks ago about the spirituality of waiting, which is part of Christian life.

01:06.338 --> 01:08.401
Our entire life in a way is waiting.

01:09.062 --> 01:11.686
Come Lord Jesus, we're waiting for him to come back.

01:12.207 --> 01:17.395
Well, you say, all right, is that just sort of a passive stance new is the short answer.

01:17.455 --> 01:20.760
There's a lot to do while we wait.

01:21.601 --> 01:23.564
And the readings illuminate that in different ways.

01:24.005 --> 01:27.250
I wanna begin with a second reading from the letter of James,

01:27.362 --> 01:29.764
which is one of my favorites in the New Testament.

01:29.845 --> 01:34.870
It's full of very practical wisdom, very quotable, very memorable.

01:34.930 --> 01:38.013
He had a great eye for the striking image.

01:38.854 --> 01:42.538
Well, listen now to this text as it begins.

01:43.959 --> 01:48.023
Be patient, brothers and sisters, until the coming of the Lord.

01:48.304 --> 01:50.446
Okay, so that's all of us all the time.

01:50.586 --> 01:51.307
We're waiting.

01:51.687 --> 01:52.468
So be patient.

01:53.529 --> 01:54.450
Here's the comparison now.

01:54.978 --> 02:05.431
See how the farmer waits for the precious fruit of the earth being patient with it until it receives the early and late rains.

02:06.613 --> 02:10.798
Some translations have the spring and winter rains.

02:12.160 --> 02:18.508
I don't know about you, but for me, the worst kind of weather is cold rain.

02:19.629 --> 02:23.474
You know, look, from the Midwest, I'm used to snow and like a snowstorm is kind of

02:23.810 --> 02:27.415
interesting, if you're not in a car while it's happening.

02:27.435 --> 02:35.487
And then the wake of a snowstorm, you know, when it gets real cold, but usually it's bright blue sky and the sun's out and the white snow and it's, you know, quite striking, really.

02:35.888 --> 02:37.550
Spring weather is, you know, can be lovely.

02:37.791 --> 02:38.772
Summer weather is great.

02:38.792 --> 02:40.334
Fall weather, terrific.

02:41.396 --> 02:51.090
The worst weather, in my opinion, would be, let's say late November and it's about 37 degrees and it's raining.

02:51.714 --> 03:01.688
It's like a summer rain can be refreshing, but a winter rain, for me, that's the worst kind of weather.

03:01.708 --> 03:03.892
Okay, now put this in a spiritual order.

03:05.955 --> 03:07.677
When do we experience winter rains?

03:09.520 --> 03:11.362
Times of enormous failure.

03:13.465 --> 03:14.767
Times of moral failure.

03:14.807 --> 03:16.590
Times of great sin in our lives.

03:18.232 --> 03:19.474
Times of sickness.

03:20.194 --> 03:29.786
I mean, of course, in my pastoral ministry, I'm always dealing with people who are struggling with sickness, people in the hospital, recovering from surgery, getting bad news from the doctor.

03:29.846 --> 03:32.770
That kind of suffering is like winter rain.

03:34.191 --> 03:37.235
The loss of a loved one, nothing is worse, right?

03:38.236 --> 03:39.197
Nothing is worse.

03:39.278 --> 03:42.922
Nothing is more like winter rain than that.

03:45.525 --> 03:49.330
So what's the comparison that James gives us?

03:49.506 --> 03:54.053
just see these things as dumb suffering.

03:54.073 --> 03:59.360
So while we're waiting for the coming of the Lord, these awful things happen to us.

04:00.182 --> 04:03.827
And everybody listening to me right now, you know exactly what I'm talking about.

04:03.847 --> 04:07.372
Unless if you're beyond the age of five, you know what I'm talking about.

04:07.913 --> 04:13.722
We all endure these really dark, painful moments, the worst kind of weather.

04:15.284 --> 04:16.786
But see, Jane is compelling us.

04:17.122 --> 04:21.929
not to see these times as just dumb suffering, but rather as the farmer does.

04:22.510 --> 04:25.194
Now, you know, I'm from outside Chicago with suburbs.

04:25.214 --> 04:30.562
I didn't know much about farms, but now in my diocese, I'm surrounded by farms and farmers.

04:31.183 --> 04:35.630
And I've had the privilege of visiting some farms and coming to know farmers better.

04:36.531 --> 04:43.762
And farmers are extraordinary people, you know, because they're very close to the earth and the rhythms of nature, but also they live in,

04:44.386 --> 04:46.908
dependence upon the weather in a way that most people don't.

04:46.928 --> 04:52.694
I mean, you plant your crop and then you're hoping for the right rhythm of sun and rain and so on.

04:53.575 --> 05:03.344
So I can be experiencing in my house, these winter rains are coming, these late season rains and it's just miserable and I gotta run to the car and I just hate it.

05:04.045 --> 05:08.489
But a farmer, he's saying, great, great.

05:09.250 --> 05:13.554
I'm delighted we're getting all this rain because this is gonna be really helpful

05:13.634 --> 05:14.415
for my crop.

05:16.277 --> 05:23.586
Be patient, James says, as the farmer is patient, while he receives the winter and spring rains, why?

05:24.206 --> 05:27.791
Because he's waiting for the precious fruit of the earth.

05:29.272 --> 05:32.937
See, what are these moments of great suffering?

05:34.318 --> 05:41.106
Can we read them as preparations for the reception of Christ in our lives?

05:41.986 --> 05:47.431
Ways the Holy Spirit is preparing us to receive the Lord when He comes.

05:48.913 --> 05:54.778
The turning over of the soil of our hearts so as to receive the gift of grace.

05:55.819 --> 06:00.464
What Foltsheen said is sometimes the Lord has to break a heart in order to get into it.

06:01.565 --> 06:03.086
Well, I think a lot of people know what that's like.

06:04.227 --> 06:08.471
It's like the winter rain that makes the growth of the crop possible.

06:09.853 --> 06:11.154
So while we wait,

06:12.034 --> 06:19.481
While we're patient, we're aware that the Lord is mysteriously at work even in the suffering we go through.

06:20.242 --> 06:23.886
Okay, so there's the first great image from James, but there's more to it.

06:24.226 --> 06:27.469
He says, you too must be patient.

06:28.350 --> 06:33.095
Make your hearts firm because the coming of the Lord is at hand.

06:33.915 --> 06:36.858
Now, heart, it's a great word in the Bible.

06:37.859 --> 06:40.722
They didn't think in terms of body and soul, that's more Greek language.

06:40.930 --> 06:42.913
But heart is a very biblical term.

06:44.115 --> 06:45.937
And it comes up into the great tradition, of course.

06:45.977 --> 06:51.606
Think of John Henry Newman, his motto, core, ad core, locary, to her heart, speaks to heart.

06:51.926 --> 06:53.488
And it's this gesture I just did here.

06:53.548 --> 06:57.554
I'm gesturing toward the organ in my chest, the heart.

06:58.055 --> 07:03.082
But it means the deepest center, right?

07:03.102 --> 07:08.370
The ground and organizing principle of the whole of my life.

07:09.058 --> 07:14.165
so mind and passions and body and feelings and sentiments and all the things that make me up.

07:14.705 --> 07:18.731
But somehow there's a center to all of that.

07:18.791 --> 07:21.674
There's my heart of hearts, we'll say.

07:21.694 --> 07:28.503
And what's the heart ultimately, is what's ordering me to God.

07:29.925 --> 07:36.914
That's why Augustine says, Lord, you made us for yourself, but our heart is restless till it rests in thee.

07:36.994 --> 07:42.319
There's the idea that the center of me wants God ultimately.

07:43.000 --> 07:49.767
And it's trying to order the whole of me toward God, if that makes sense.

07:49.787 --> 07:51.168
And so what's the recommendation here?

07:52.029 --> 07:55.833
Make your hearts firm as you wait.

07:56.774 --> 07:58.256
See, what happens everybody?

07:58.616 --> 08:04.402
Well, we're waiting for the coming of the Lord, meaning we're waiting for what's gonna fulfill us ultimately.

08:05.058 --> 08:05.899
And it's hard.

08:06.039 --> 08:06.540
I get it.

08:06.660 --> 08:07.261
It's hard.

08:07.321 --> 08:09.964
That's why it's restless in this life.

08:10.385 --> 08:13.188
Nothing in this world satisfies us ultimately.

08:13.709 --> 08:15.030
Everything is even essence.

08:15.130 --> 08:16.572
Everything comes and goes.

08:17.253 --> 08:19.195
Our feelings rise and fall.

08:19.255 --> 08:20.096
They come and go.

08:20.197 --> 08:24.221
Our bodies develop and then they deteriorate.

08:24.261 --> 08:25.984
I mean, that's just life is like.

08:28.727 --> 08:34.514
While we're waiting amidst all of this, you know, fluctuation, keep your

08:34.818 --> 08:36.820
heart, firm.

08:37.440 --> 08:39.142
That's really, really good advice.

08:40.283 --> 08:52.495
So even as age, and even as you get weaker, and even as you endure failure, and even as things come and go, your heart is focused on the Lord.

08:53.476 --> 08:57.559
Think here of Teresa of Abuela's great image of the interior castle.

08:57.619 --> 08:58.620
That's really good, isn't it?

08:58.740 --> 08:59.281
The castle.

09:00.062 --> 09:01.223
It's a keep.

09:01.243 --> 09:02.324
It's a fortress.

09:02.984 --> 09:04.626
It's a place of safety.

09:06.306 --> 09:09.369
and it's in the heart, it's the interior castle.

09:10.130 --> 09:17.257
So even as things are coming and going and battle's raging around you, you're safe in this interior castle.

09:19.019 --> 09:19.699
Keep it firm.

09:19.759 --> 09:20.540
Now, how do you do that?

09:21.621 --> 09:24.344
It's a great advent theme now, prayer above all.

09:26.005 --> 09:28.588
Don't just think, I'm going to piously mutter my prayers.

09:28.928 --> 09:31.951
I mean, that might be a propodetic to real prayer.

09:32.492 --> 09:34.674
Prayer is this

09:35.266 --> 09:39.171
raising of the mind and the heart to God.

09:39.231 --> 09:40.633
That's John of Damascus.

09:42.295 --> 09:47.441
It's keeping the heart fixed upon God in season and out.

09:47.982 --> 09:50.385
It's really, really good advent advice.

09:51.286 --> 09:51.566
Okay.

09:52.067 --> 09:53.909
And here's the third thing from James.

09:53.989 --> 10:02.920
I love he's then says, do not complain brothers and sisters about one another that you may not be judged.

10:04.002 --> 10:04.242
Look,

10:04.866 --> 10:07.569
I'm a sinner, you're a sinner, everyone listening is a sinner.

10:07.609 --> 10:08.810
So we know what this is about.

10:09.851 --> 10:12.313
This is okay, I'm waiting for the Lord.

10:12.353 --> 10:14.476
I'm not fulfilled.

10:15.196 --> 10:17.238
Nothing in this world will fulfill me.

10:17.398 --> 10:20.241
Everything ultimately is kind of frustrating to me.

10:20.261 --> 10:22.624
I know that's life, I get it.

10:22.704 --> 10:23.625
That's what life is like.

10:23.705 --> 10:26.648
Even the best moments will they come and they go.

10:26.668 --> 10:27.929
All right, all right.

10:28.449 --> 10:29.270
So what's the danger?

10:30.011 --> 10:33.074
The danger is in the midst of that frustration,

10:34.626 --> 10:35.507
I start looking around.

10:38.271 --> 10:39.553
How come she's getting so much credit?

10:39.573 --> 10:40.554
I'm better than she is.

10:41.716 --> 10:44.560
That guy, you're giving that job to that guy?

10:45.281 --> 10:46.803
I mean, I'm much better than he is.

10:48.164 --> 10:50.047
Why is he getting favored over there?

10:50.528 --> 10:51.469
And they're ignoring me.

10:51.549 --> 11:02.204
What happens into all of us sinners is we kind of lose sight of where we're going of what God wants following God's will.

11:02.284 --> 11:03.986
And so then we look around.

11:04.418 --> 11:07.502
Now go right back, if you want, to Cain and Abel.

11:07.783 --> 11:09.125
See, the Bible knew all about this.

11:09.165 --> 11:22.363
The Bible knows about it all from Genesis to Revelation, but it begins with Cain and Abel, is when they lose sight of God, you know, accepted Abel's sacrifice, how can we accept my sacrifice?

11:23.424 --> 11:26.388
And it leads to this jealousy, to the point of murder.

11:28.311 --> 11:30.154
Welcome to the dynamics of human life.

11:30.654 --> 11:33.298
Read any book of history you're gonna see

11:33.506 --> 11:34.548
something like this.

11:35.309 --> 11:36.310
So what's James telling us?

11:37.652 --> 11:39.595
Don't complain about each other.

11:40.216 --> 11:40.917
Get over it.

11:41.338 --> 11:43.121
It's a waste of time spiritually.

11:43.782 --> 11:47.728
Keep your eyes, your heart fixed on the Lord.

11:48.149 --> 11:50.152
Keep waiting for the Lord.

11:50.212 --> 11:54.158
And don't look around at everybody else.

11:54.478 --> 11:58.825
Remember, I think I've told this in Dante's Divine Comedy, the envious and Mount Purgatory.

11:59.867 --> 12:01.970
Have their eyelids sewn shut.

12:02.658 --> 12:07.585
And it's the way in the middle ages of falcon or would have sown the eyelids of the falcon shut.

12:08.606 --> 12:09.868
It's great in that, isn't it?

12:10.429 --> 12:12.211
Because that's what envious people do.

12:12.932 --> 12:14.054
We look around, look around.

12:15.155 --> 12:16.137
Stop looking around.

12:16.437 --> 12:19.081
Keep the eyes of your heart fixed on the Lord.

12:19.261 --> 12:20.563
See, and don't play that game.

12:21.724 --> 12:22.666
I love this too, finally.

12:23.327 --> 12:26.491
He says, take an example of hardship and patience.

12:26.952 --> 12:31.538
Take as an example of hardship and patience the prophets who spoke in the name of the Lord.

12:31.778 --> 12:35.422
You know, the author James knows perfectly well.

12:37.043 --> 12:50.376
All the patriarchs, Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Moses, Joshua, Saul, Samuel, David, Solomon, Jeremiah, Isaiah, Ezekiel, I don't know any exception to this rule.

12:50.837 --> 12:53.499
Every one of them endured hardships.

12:54.561 --> 13:00.146
There's not one figure in the Old Testament or a New Testament that didn't endure some terrible hardship.

13:00.898 --> 13:05.303
It's just kind of written into the structure of our finite and fallen existence.

13:06.945 --> 13:08.067
What do we notice in them?

13:08.127 --> 13:09.148
What do we admire in them?

13:10.590 --> 13:12.072
They're patients under trial.

13:12.873 --> 13:15.576
Now, go from the biblical patriarchs to all the saints.

13:16.117 --> 13:16.958
Give me an example.

13:17.198 --> 13:30.354
You can't find one, trust me, of a saint who didn't go through some trial, some difficulty and who found their sanctity precisely in their patients through suffering.

13:31.714 --> 13:38.481
Look at the Bible, look at the great saints and take courage and direction from the way they handled hardship.

13:39.082 --> 13:41.104
Can I give you just one more as I'm running out of time?

13:41.545 --> 13:45.329
And I want to look just briefly at the first reading from Isaiah.

13:46.090 --> 13:52.938
And he's waiting for the Lord to come and the step will flower and this great day is coming.

13:53.458 --> 13:54.960
But what do we do while we're waiting?

13:55.180 --> 14:00.626
He says, strengthen the hands that are feeble, make firm the knees that are weak.

14:00.802 --> 14:07.131
What I love here, and I'll close with it, is never ever think of this waiting as some dumbly passive thing.

14:07.191 --> 14:09.474
I'm just waiting, I'm just waiting.

14:09.494 --> 14:09.875
No, no, no.

14:11.176 --> 14:12.839
It's an active waiting.

14:13.580 --> 14:15.102
It's an anticipation.

14:15.683 --> 14:20.189
So think of the hands and the legs and you're ready for action.

14:20.729 --> 14:25.136
Your expectation of the Lord doesn't make you passive.

14:25.636 --> 14:29.842
It draws you up out of yourself in a active anticipation.

14:30.338 --> 14:39.691
Just the saints, would it ever occur to you that Thomas Aquinas, or Francis of Assisi, or Teresa of this year, or John Paul II were not energetic?

14:40.772 --> 14:50.786
On the contrary, their powers and energies were strengthened and awakened precisely by their expectation of the Lord.

14:51.047 --> 14:56.434
So wait with this active, joyful anticipation.

14:57.026 --> 15:03.418
So take a look everybody at these readings and you get a really good sense of what to do while you wait.

15:04.099 --> 15:04.700
And God bless you.

15:09.449 --> 15:13.036
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

15:13.437 --> 15:18.546
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

